      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If healthcare is established as a fundamental human right, then arguments against it based purely on \"government inefficiency\" become secondary to the moral obligation to provide care. The focus then shifts from whether the government *can* manage it efficiently to how it can best fulfill its duty to its citizens. In a civilized society committed to human rights, the perceived inefficiencies of a system are a problem to be solved, not a justification for denying basic medical needs.",
      "source": "target",
